<p><b>Lewis Mumford</b> (<a href="/wiki/October_19" title="October 19">October 19</a>, <a href="/wiki/1895" title="1895">1895</a> – <a href="/wiki/January_26" title="January 26">January 26</a>, <a href="/wiki/1990" title="1990">1990</a>) was an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Historian" title="Historian">historian</a> of <a href="/wiki/Technology" title="Technology">technology</a> and <a href="/wiki/Science" title="Science">science</a>. Particularly noted for his study of <a href="/wiki/City" title="City">cities</a> and urban architecture, he had a tremendously broad career as a writer that also included a period as an influential <a href="/wiki/Literary_critic" title="Literary critic" class="mw-redirect">literary critic</a>. Mumford was influenced by the work of Scottish theorist Sir <a href="/wiki/Patrick_Geddes" title="Patrick Geddes">Patrick Geddes</a>.</p>
<p>Mumford was also a contemporary and friend of <a href="/wiki/Frank_Lloyd_Wright" title="Frank Lloyd Wright">Frank Lloyd Wright</a>, <a href="/wiki/Frederic_Osborn" title="Frederic Osborn">Frederic J. Osborn</a>, <a href="/wiki/Edmund_Bacon_(architect)" title="Edmund Bacon (architect)">Edmund N. Bacon</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Vannevar_Bush" title="Vannevar Bush">Vannevar Bush</a>.</p>
